$n-1 < \dfrac{23}{7} - n \le n$

We can split this into two inequalities:
1) $n-1 < \dfrac{23}{7} - n$
$2n < \dfrac{23}{7} + 1$
$2n < \dfrac{23+7}{7}$
$2n < \dfrac{30}{7}$
$n < \dfrac{15}{7}$
Since $\dfrac{15}{7} \approx 2.14$, we have $n \le 2$.

2) $\dfrac{23}{7} - n \le n$
$\dfrac{23}{7} \le 2n$
$n \ge \dfrac{23}{14}$
Since $\dfrac{23}{14} \approx 1.64$, we have $n \ge 2$.

Combining the two inequalities for $n$, we have $n \le 2$ and $n \ge 2$.
Since $n$ must be an integer (as it is the ceiling of $x$), the only possible integer value for $n$ is $n=2$.

Now substitute $n=2$ back into the equation for $x$:
$x = \dfrac{23}{7} - n$
$x = \dfrac{23}{7} - 2$
$x = \dfrac{23}{7} - \dfrac{14}{7}$
$x = \dfrac{23-14}{7}$
$x = \dfrac{9}{7}$

Let's verify this solution.
If $x = \dfrac{9}{7}$, then $\lceil x \rceil = \lceil \dfrac{9}{7} \rceil = \lceil 1 \dfrac{2}{7} \rceil = 2$.
Then $\lceil x \rceil + x = 2 + \dfrac{9}{7} = \dfrac{14}{7} + \dfrac{9}{7} = \dfrac{23}{7}$.
This matches the given equation.

The final answer is $\dfrac{9}{7}$.

